 egin{theorem}[Supporting theorem S2: compact monotone endpoint family]\label{thm:interval}
For every \(\lambda\ge0\), \(I(\lambda)\) is nonempty and compact; writing \(L(\lambda)=\min I(\lambda)\) and \(U(\lambda)=\max I(\lambda)\), the map \(\lambda\mapsto L(\lambda)\) is nonincreasing, \(\lambda\mapsto U(\lambda)\) is nondecreasing, and \(I(\lambda)\subseteq I(\lambda')\) whenever \(\lambda\le\lambda'\) in the sense \([L(\lambda),U(\lambda)]\subseteq[L(\lambda'),U(\lambda')]\). Moreover \(L(0)=U(0)=	heta_{\mathrm{FD}}\).
\end{theorem}
 egin{proof}
Fix \(\lambda\ge0\) and work on the canonical support \(\mathcal U=\{1,\dots,5\}\). Let \(\mathcal F(P,\lambda)\) be the set of tuples \((\pi,w_0,w_1,\varphi)\) satisfying the simplex constraints \(\pi,w_0,w_1\in\Delta(\mathcal U)\), the box constraints \(0\le \varphi(m,x,u)\le 1\), the Bayes equalities \(\pi=p_0w_0+p_1w_1\), the four compatibility equations \eqref{eq:compat}, and the leak inequalities \(|\varphi(m,1,u)-\varphi(m,0,u)|\le \lambda\). This feasible set is contained in the compact product space \(\Delta(\mathcal U)^3	imes[0,1]^{20}\). Every defining equality or inequality is continuous in the coordinates, so \(\mathcal F(P,\lambda)\) is closed. Hence \(\mathcal F(P,\lambda)\) is compact.

The set is nonempty. The explicit construction used in Theorem~ef{thm:collapse} is feasible at \(\lambda=0\), and the same tuple is feasible for every larger \(\lambda\) because the leak restriction is then weaker. Therefore \(\mathcal F(P,\lambda)
eq\varnothing\) for all \(\lambda\ge0\).

The causal objective \(	heta(\pi,w_0,w_1,\varphi)\) from \eqref{eq:ace} is continuous in the coordinates. Consequently \(I(\lambda)=	heta igl(\mathcal F(P,\lambda) igr)\) is the continuous image of a compact set, hence compact. In particular the extrema \(L(\lambda)=\min I(\lambda)\) and \(U(\lambda)=\max I(\lambda)\) exist.

Now let \(0\le \lambda\le \lambda'\). Every tuple feasible at level \(\lambda\) also satisfies the weaker inequalities \(|\varphi(m,1,u)-\varphi(m,0,u)|\le \lambda'\), so \(\mathcal F(P,\lambda)\subseteq \mathcal F(P,\lambda')\). Applying the continuous objective gives \(I(\lambda)\subseteq I(\lambda')\). Therefore the minimum over the larger set cannot exceed the minimum over the smaller set, and the maximum over the larger set cannot be below the maximum over the smaller set: \(L(\lambda')\le L(\lambda)\) and \(U(\lambda)\le U(\lambda')\). Equivalently, \(\lambda\mapsto L(\lambda)\) is nonincreasing, \(\lambda\mapsto U(\lambda)\) is nondecreasing, and \([L(\lambda),U(\lambda)]\subseteq [L(\lambda'),U(\lambda')]\).

Finally, Theorem~ef{thm:collapse} shows that \(I(0)=\{	heta_{\mathrm{FD}}\}\). Hence \(L(0)=U(0)=	heta_{\mathrm{FD}}\).
\end{proof}
